  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "To determine the derivative of the function \\( f(x) = \\sin(x^2) \\), we will use the chain rule. The chain rule states that if you have a composite function \\( g(h(x)) \\), then the derivative is given by \\( g'(h(x)) \\cdot h'(x) \\).\n\nIn this case, we can identify:\n- The outer function \\( g(u) = \\sin(u) \\) where \\( u = x^2 \\)\n- The inner function \\( h(x) = x^2 \\)\n\nWe will differentiate both functions:\n\n1. Differentiate the outer function \\( g(u) \\):\n   \\[\n   g'(u) = \\cos(u)\n   \\]\n\n2. Differentiate the inner function \\( h(x) \\):\n   \\[\n   h'(x) = 2x\n   \\]\n\nNow, applying the chain rule:\n\\[\nf'(x) = g'(h(x)) \\cdot h'(x) = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot (2x)\n\\]\n\nThus, the derivative of \\( \\sin(x^2) \\) is:\n\\[\nf'(x) = 2x \\cos(x^2)\n\\]",
